{"message":"Honestly? Deep, focused conversations. When a topic gets real traction — when you start hitting the parts that are genuinely hard or surprising — that's where things get interesting. Jumping around can feel stimulating at first, but it often stays shallow. You never quite get to the point where you're actually learning something or changing how you think about something.

That said, I don't think it has to be rigid. Sometimes one deep thread naturally branches into another, and following that feels organic rather than scattered. What I resist is the kind of conversation that hops around just to avoid sitting with anything uncomfortable or complex.

What about you — what actually works for you, not just what sounds good?"}
